1
00:00:05,490 --> 00:00:08,232
Welcome to the course
on Plasma Physics and Applications.

2
00:00:08,696 --> 00:00:11,433
Today we will continue our discussion
on thermonuclear fusion

3
00:00:11,433 --> 00:00:13,099
by taking a very simple approach

4
00:00:13,099 --> 00:00:16,138
to design the main elements
of a magnetic fusion reactor.

5
00:00:16,736 --> 00:00:20,485
We have seen together what
the main elements are for the reactor,

6
00:00:20,837 --> 00:00:24,740
but we're now ready to really define
the key design parameters.

7
00:00:25,390 --> 00:00:29,492
The design parameters result from
constraints that are coming

8
00:00:29,492 --> 00:00:32,585
from engineering,
but also from nuclear physics.

9
00:00:33,042 --> 00:00:36,745
And this will be combined with the need
to minimize the cost of electricity

10
00:00:36,745 --> 00:00:41,783
to lead to a generic,
and very simple design of a reactor.

11
00:00:42,635 --> 00:00:45,465
I'd like to start the discussion
by reminding ourselves

12
00:00:45,465 --> 00:00:49,582
what the schematic is of a fusion reactor,
at least as we anticipate it today.

13
00:00:50,242 --> 00:00:53,574
In general, we have fuels
that come in from outside

14
00:00:53,574 --> 00:00:56,048
in the form of deuterium and lithium.

15
00:00:57,187 --> 00:01:00,368
They'll be injected to the system.

16
00:01:00,843 --> 00:01:04,123
The deuterium
will be going into the plasma,

17
00:01:04,649 --> 00:01:06,566
which will form the core of the reactor.

18
00:01:06,566 --> 00:01:09,321
The lithium will be part of
what we call the <i>blanket</i>.

19
00:01:09,627 --> 00:01:12,024
I remind you that the blanket
has two main jobs.

20
00:01:12,679 --> 00:01:15,362
First it has to get the heat

21
00:01:15,362 --> 00:01:18,027
from the neutrons issued
by the fusion reactions.

22
00:01:18,887 --> 00:01:20,888
The heat will be collected
in a heat exchanger,

23
00:01:20,888 --> 00:01:24,870
and therefore will be used to generate
electricity by a steam generator.

24
00:01:25,110 --> 00:01:29,748
And second, the blanket
needs to be producing tritium.

25
00:01:30,879 --> 00:01:32,964
The tritium will be produced
by the reactions between

26
00:01:32,964 --> 00:01:37,017
the neutrons issued by
the DT fusion reactions themselves,

27
00:01:37,518 --> 00:01:39,937
and the lithium that
will be present in the blanket.

28
00:01:39,937 --> 00:01:43,330
So the tritium, once more,
will be only present

29
00:01:43,330 --> 00:01:47,320
in a closed loop within the reactor,

30
00:01:47,320 --> 00:01:52,680
it will not come in from outside,
nor will it go out from the reactor.

31
00:01:53,485 --> 00:01:55,469
So this is a generic scheme,

32
00:01:55,469 --> 00:02:00,557
with the plasma forming the hot core,
of course, of the whole system,

33
00:02:00,842 --> 00:02:04,862
but as we said in previous lectures,
we will concentrate in this course

34
00:02:04,862 --> 00:02:07,549
mostly on the magnetic fusion approach,

35
00:02:07,549 --> 00:02:11,333
and that is the approach in which
we confine a plasma using magnetic fields,

36
00:02:11,333 --> 00:02:14,720
so we need to consider
that around the plasma

37
00:02:14,720 --> 00:02:18,322
not only will there be a blanket,
but it will also be a magnet,

38
00:02:18,700 --> 00:02:24,610
as illustrated in this 3D view
of a fusion reactor,

39
00:02:24,610 --> 00:02:28,636
a magnet that then will produce the field
with which we'll confine the plasma.

40
00:02:29,906 --> 00:02:33,868
We have said in the previous lecture
that the first reactors will operate

41
00:02:33,868 --> 00:02:37,426
between what we call <i>breakeven</i>
and what we call <i>ignition</i>.

42
00:02:37,426 --> 00:02:41,565
I remind you that breakeven is a situation
in which the fusion power

43
00:02:41,565 --> 00:02:46,462
produced by the plasma
is exactly equal to the input power,

44
00:02:46,462 --> 00:02:51,429
so the capital Q,
which is the fusion gain, is equal to 1.

45
00:02:51,993 --> 00:02:56,299
Ignition is a situation in which there is
no input power from outside at all,

46
00:02:56,299 --> 00:02:59,920
and so all the heating from the plasma
comes from the alpha particle produced

47
00:02:59,920 --> 00:03:02,045
by the fusion reactions themselves,

48
00:03:02,045 --> 00:03:04,785
so that corresponds
to a fusion gain of infinity.

49
00:03:05,695 --> 00:03:09,870
In terms of the confinement quality,

50
00:03:10,769 --> 00:03:16,642
we can quantify that as the product
of the density of the plasma,

51
00:03:16,642 --> 00:03:20,955
and the confinement time
for the energy, n times 𝜏E,

52
00:03:20,955 --> 00:03:26,908
and for the two situations we have
about 1x10²⁰ m⁻³s for breakeven,

53
00:03:26,908 --> 00:03:32,496
and six times that,
that is 6x10²⁰ m⁻³s for ignition,

54
00:03:32,496 --> 00:03:35,049
so we'll be in-between these two values.

55
00:03:35,472 --> 00:03:39,253
Of course, together with the value n 𝜏E

56
00:03:39,253 --> 00:03:43,993
we need to have a temperature
that's large enough

57
00:03:43,993 --> 00:03:48,344
for the fusion reactions
to take place, typically 10-15 keV.

58
00:03:49,923 --> 00:03:53,678
What are the design goals
we are considering for this exercise?

59
00:03:54,184 --> 00:03:56,881
What we like to do is to minimize
the cost of the reactor,

60
00:03:56,881 --> 00:04:00,498
because that will correspond
to minimizing the cost of electricity.

61
00:04:01,442 --> 00:04:03,685
We also like to minimize the requirements

62
00:04:03,685 --> 00:04:06,967
that the design imposes
on the plasma performance.

63
00:04:06,967 --> 00:04:10,224
We know it's difficult to confine
the energy and the particles

64
00:04:10,224 --> 00:04:13,990
in the plasma for a long time,
so we don't want to make it more difficult

65
00:04:13,990 --> 00:04:18,688
by imposing too large values for 𝜏E,

66
00:04:18,938 --> 00:04:20,944
the confinement time for the energy.

67
00:04:20,944 --> 00:04:23,470
It's also difficult
to hold the plasma stable

68
00:04:24,885 --> 00:04:28,548
if the plasma has very large pressure.

69
00:04:28,711 --> 00:04:31,614
That is the β of the plasma,

70
00:04:31,614 --> 00:04:33,508
which is the ratio
between the plasma pressure

71
00:04:33,508 --> 00:04:35,672
and the magnetic field pressure,

72
00:04:36,521 --> 00:04:40,761
has to be as small as we can
from the engineering point of view,

73
00:04:40,761 --> 00:04:43,821
in order not to make it
too difficult for plasma physics.

74
00:04:43,916 --> 00:04:45,270
So these are the goals.

75
00:04:45,840 --> 00:04:49,897
What we need to optimize are the size
and the geometry of the reactor,

76
00:04:50,202 --> 00:04:52,504
and the value of the intensity
of the magnetic field

77
00:04:52,504 --> 00:04:54,198
that will provide the confinement.

78
00:04:55,170 --> 00:04:58,830
In a somewhat more sophisticated
part of the exercise,

79
00:04:58,830 --> 00:05:02,125
